<font color="#FF0000">TO CHARLES</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jan  4 13:33:07 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Charles,<br><br>
Thanks for your response.<br><br>
My point is this: Diem was not President because of the will of the Vietnamese people. <br><br>
There are far too many who believe that Diem's *assassination* was approved by Kennedy. I don't think there is concrete evidence to that effect.<br><br>
If it WAS true is this the way the United States should conduct its business? By assassination? <br><br>
It was true, however, that his removal was ordered by Washington, which once again, demonstrates how little &quot;say&quot; the people of South Vietnam had in their own affairs and who was to govern their nation.<br><br>
As far as the timetable you suggest and when protests began ie. whether or not Diem was still in office, you are missing my point. People who eventually became disillusioned with the war could read history.<br><br>
In 1962 the American people were told by Robert MacNamara, that the war would be finished in 6 months to a year. Later on, Gen Westmoreland proclaimed he could see the &quot;light at the end of the tunnel&quot;. Lyndon Johnson (who must have believed all the propaganda spewed by the press after Tet 1968) decided he could not stomach the war he escalated any longer. Many people fail to understand why people questioned leaders who lied to them and were not willing to follow them into the quagmire.<br><br>

